Histology of the liver and pancreas 

Sunday, September 24, 2017 

2:32 PM 

Liver 

The liver is positioned to collect blood from the portal system, which drains the GIT tract, pancreas and spleen.  

Functions: 

-Metabolise, detoxify and inactivate endogenous and exogenous compounds 

-Act as a filter for aging erythrocytes, bacteria, parasites through Kupffer cells 

-Convert some hormones and vitamins into an active form 

-Production of bile 

-Synthesis of glucose, plasma proteins, cholesterol, fatty acids, phospholipids 

 

80% of the liver volume is composed of hepatocytes, which are secretory epithelial cells separating the lumen of the bile canaliculi from the fenestrated endothelium of the vascular sinusoids. Both the basolateral membrane (vascular side) and apical membrane (canaliculi side) have microvilli. The endothelial cells are fenestrated, allowing solutes but preventing cells from passing into the space of Disse. Other cells include Kupffer cells (fixed macrophages) and Ito cells (for vitamin A storage).  

 

Blood supply to the liver involves supply from the portal vein (75%) and supply from the hepatic artery (25%).  

 

Bile flow occurs from tiny canaliculi formed at apical junctions, to perilobular ducts, to interlobular ducts, to the bile duct. 

 

 

Functional view of liver structure 

 

 

Note that hepatocytes have distinctly round nuclei, with each cell having one or two. Most cells have one, but binucleate cells are common. 

 

Pancreas 

Exocrine pancreas 

Each pancreatic acinus is made of a circular arrangement of pyramidal secretory cells around a duct. Duct cells modify the secretion by secreting NaHCO3. Goblet cells present in the ducts produce mucus. Exocrine cells contain darker secretory granules. 

 

Endocrine pancreas 

Clusters of cells known as Islets of Langerhans surround arteries and secrete hormones into the blood. The cell types are: 

-Alpha cells for glucagon 

-Beta cells for insulin 

-Delta cells for somatostatin 

-F cells for pancreatic polypeptide 

 

Differentiation between these cells require special stains, but we know that most cells are beta cells.
